---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
---
<Layout title="Limitations" description="Known limitations, open questions, and what HeadGenome does not claim.">
<div class="page-hero">
  <p class="overline">Limitations & Open Questions</p>
  <h1>What we don't claim.</h1>
  <p>A visible limitations section is a credibility signal, not a weakness. These are real constraints on the current results.</p>
</div>

<div class="section">
  <div class="limit-list">

    <div class="limit-item reveal">
      <div class="limit-icon">🔬</div>
      <div>
        <h3>Models up to 1.5B parameters</h3>
        <p>All causal ablation and KV-cache experiments were run on models ≤ 1.5B parameters. Whether the same four-class taxonomy holds at 7B, 70B, or 400B is an open empirical question. The V/Q scaling law appears in every architecture we tested, but extrapolation to frontier-scale models is untested.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="limit-item reveal">
      <div class="limit-icon">📊</div>
      <p class="overline">Important distinction</p>
      <div>
        <h3>FLOP savings are theoretical projections</h3>
        <p>The 4–8× FLOP savings numbers are FLOP-model projections — mathematically grounded in real measured head fractions, but not measured wall-clock speedups. Realising these projections requires a sparse kernel backend (FlexAttention or custom CUDA). The current PyTorch-mask reference backend adds overhead rather than reducing it.</p>
        <p style="margin-top:.75rem">The <strong>13.3× KV-cache compression</strong> was directly measured on Llama-3.2-1B hardware.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="limit-item reveal">
      <div class="limit-icon">📉</div>
      <div>
        <h3>Rare head counts are small</h3>
        <p>Retrieval heads are rare (1–13 per model). Statistical conclusions about Retrieval head behaviour rest on small sample sizes within each architecture. Cross-architecture consistency is strong, but within-architecture variance estimates have wide confidence intervals.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="limit-item reveal">
      <div class="limit-icon">🔀</div>
      <div>
        <h3>Hyper-diagonal heads are unresolved</h3>
        <p>A small number of heads (≈1–2% in GPT-2 Medium) sit at the boundary between Local and Retrieval on the V/Q axis. These "hyper-diagonal" heads exhibit context-dependent switching between local and global attention patterns. They are classified as Local by our probe but may warrant a fifth class in a more refined taxonomy.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="limit-item reveal">
      <div class="limit-icon">🧪</div>
      <div>
        <h3>KV geometry is qualitative only</h3>
        <p>The PCA projections in Figure 12 are a qualitative illustration of geometric structure, not a quantitative proof. PCA explained variance is typically 30–55% in 3D — substantial geometric information is discarded. The untrained control panel is the key control, but positional encoding contamination of the projection cannot be fully ruled out.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="limit-item reveal">
      <div class="limit-icon">🌐</div>
      <div>
        <h3>GQA head-indexing caveat</h3>
        <p>For GQA models (Qwen, Llama), KV-cache head indices map to KV-groups, not to individual query heads. Our analysis correctly maps through the group structure (<code>kv_head = query_head // group_size</code>), but this means the effective granularity of head-level analysis is coarser in GQA architectures than in MHA architectures like GPT-2.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

  </div>
</div>
</Layout>

<style>
.section { max-width:860px; margin:0 auto; padding:3rem 2.5rem 6rem; }
.overline { font-size:.75rem; font-weight:700; letter-spacing:.1em; text-transform:uppercase; color:var(--muted); margin-bottom:1.5rem; display:block; }
.limit-list { display:flex; flex-direction:column; gap:2rem; }
.limit-item {
  background: var(--surface); border: 1px solid var(--border);
  border-radius: var(--radius); padding: 1.75rem;
  display: flex; gap: 1.25rem; align-items: flex-start;
}
.limit-icon { font-size:1.75rem; flex-shrink:0; }
.limit-item h3 { font-size:1rem; font-weight:700; margin-bottom:.5rem; }
.limit-item p { font-size:.9rem; color:var(--muted); line-height:1.65; }
</style>
